05680nam a22008175i 9783110783438DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107834387 a10.1515/97831107834382doi  a(DE-B1597)617515  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0042002bisacsh02aA Companion to Anticlassicisms in the Cinquecento /ced. by Marc Föcking, Susanne A. Friede, Florian Mehltretter, Angela Oster. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (VIII, 332 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aClassicism and Beyond / Il classicismo e oltre ,x2940-0074 ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Four Types of Anti-classicism -- t1 Explicit Anti-classicism -- t2 Implicit Anti-classicism -- t3 Alternative Classicism -- t4 Benvenuto Cellini as a Paradigm of Para-classicism in the Cinquecento -- tBibliography -- tIndex nominum0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  a'Anticlassicisms,' as a plural, react to the many possible forms of 'classicisms.' In the sixteenth century, classicist tendencies range from humanist traditions focusing on Horace and the teachings of rhetoric, via Pietro Bembo's canonization of a 'second antiquity' in the works of the fourteenth-century classics, Petrarch and Boccaccio, to the Aristotelianism of the second half of the century. Correspondingly, the various tendencies to destabilize or to subvert or contradict these manifold and historically dynamic 'classicisms' need to be distinguished as so many 'anticlassicisms'. This volume, after discussing the history and possible implications of the label 'anticlassicism' in Renaissance studies, differentiates and analyzes these 'anticlassicisms.' It distinguishes the various forms of opposition to 'classicisms' as to their scope (on a scale between radical poetological dissension to merely sectorial opposition in a given literary genre) and to their alternative models, be they authors (like Dante) or texts. At the same time, the various chapters specify the degree of difference or erosion inherent in anticlassicist tendencies with respect to their 'classicist' counterparts, ranging from implicit 'system disturbances' to open, intended antagonism (as in Bernesque poetry), with a view to establishing an overall picture of this field of phenomena for the first time.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by FWF  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aAntiklassizismus. 4aItalien / Kultur. 4aItalienische Kulturgeschichte. 4aKlassizismus. 4aRenaissance. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh  aAnticlassicism.  aClassicism.  aItalian Cultural History.  aRenaissance.1 aCazzato, Matteo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFliege, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriede, Susanne A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriede, Susanne A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriede, Susanne A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFöcking, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFöcking, Marc, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLiberman, Avi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLombardi, Giulia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMehltretter, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMehltretter, Florian, eeditor.4edt4ht